Density dependence

Eric R. Scott

2020-09-13

Last compiled: 2020-09-16

1 Purpose

Start by looking for density dependence on growth, survival, and reproduction in continuous forests using the number of plants in the same grid-cell as a metric for density.

2 Load Data

ha <- read_rds(here("analysis", "data", "derived_data", "ha_density.rds"))
ha
ha <-
  ha %>% 
  group_by(ha_id_number) %>% 
  arrange(ha_id_number, year) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  #scale year
  mutate(year_post = year - min(year))

Filter to just continuous forest

ha_cf <- 
  ha %>% 
  filter(habitat == "CF") %>% 
  mutate(log_shts = log(shts),
         log_shts_next = log(shts_next))

Or filter to just 1-ha and cf

ha_sub <-
  ha %>% 
  filter(habitat %in% c("CF", "1-ha")) %>% 
  mutate(log_shts = log(shts),
         log_shts_next = log(shts_next),
         habitat = as.factor(habitat))

I dont know what a height of 0 means Height of 0 probably means it was knocked over, or very small, or dead.

3 General model structure

For each vital rate Ill include the number of shoots and habitat as fixed effects and plant ID and year as random effects. Im not including plot since there are few plots in each habitat type, and preliminary modeling shows the variance for plot is the lowest of those three random effects.

ha_sub %>% 
  group_by(habitat) %>% 
  summarize(length(unique(plot)))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

4 Growth

For this Im going to use shoot number. Very closely related to height, but better behaved distribution and not sensitive to plants being knocked over.

4.1 Distribution

Number of shoots is discrete, but not really count data. Ill try a poisson distribution and a lognormal distribution.

mpois <- glmer(shts_next ~ log_shts + habitat + density_0_10 + density_10_20 + (1|ha_id_number) + (1|year_post),
                family = poisson(link = "log"),
                data = ha_sub)
boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
check_overdispersion(mpois2) #actually underdispersed
# Overdispersion test

       dispersion ratio =     0.431
  Pearson's Chi-Squared = 13470.420
                p-value =         1
No overdispersion detected.
mnorm <- glmer(shts_next ~ log_shts + habitat + density_0_10 + density_10_20 + (1|ha_id_number) + (1|year_post),
                family = gaussian(link = "log"),
                data = ha_sub)
Model failed to converge with max|grad| = 0.00462279 (tol = 0.002, component 1)Model is nearly unidentifiable: very large eigenvalue
 - Rescale variables?

But how bad is this convergence failure?

Is the max|grad| calculation correct?

max(pmin(abs(sc_grad1),abs(derivs1$gradient)))
[1] 3.231112e-06

No, its actually a lot smaller than tol, so nothing to worry about

AICtab(mpois, mnorm)

mnorm    0.0 8 
mpois 2291.2 7 
compare_performance(mpois, mnorm, rank = TRUE)
Random effect variances not available. Returned R2 does not account for random effects.

# Comparison of Model Performance Indices

Model |     Type |      AIC |      BIC | R2_marginal | RMSE |   BF | Performance_Score
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
mpois | glmerMod | 99752.70 | 99811.15 |        0.37 | 0.64 | 1.00 |            50.00%
mnorm | glmerMod | 97461.45 | 97528.26 |        0.11 | 1.07 |  Inf |            50.00%

Model mpois (of class glmerMod) performed best with an overall performance score of 50.00%.

Lognormal distribution fits best according to AIC, although poisson has lower RMSE. I guess despite being discrete, this isnt really count data per se. The lognormal model doesnt have problems with singularity that the poisson model has. Both have problems with heteroscedasticity. Ill go with log-normal.

m_growth <- mnorm
x<-check_heteroscedasticity(m_growth)
Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p = 0.000).
plot(x)

4.3 Does density matter beyond immediate surroundings?

Anova(m_growth)
Analysis of Deviance Table (Type II Wald chisquare tests)

Response: shts_next
                  Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)    
log_shts      8360.7681  1  < 2.2e-16 ***
habitat         16.7237  1  4.324e-05 ***
density_0_10     2.3961  1    0.12164    
density_10_20    7.3357  1    0.00676 ** 
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Odd, density further out is significant, but density close is not.

fixef(m_growth) %>% exp()
  (Intercept)      log_shts     habitatCF  density_0_10 density_10_20 
     1.450736      1.848362      1.036624      1.000115      1.000444

Both weakly positive density dependence

5 Survival

Pre-reproductive census, so plants live/die in same year as shts and ht

m_surv <- glmer(surv ~ log_shts + habitat + density_0_10 + density_10_20 + (1|ha_id_number) + (1|year), 
                family = binomial, data = ha_sub)
Model is nearly unidentifiable: very large eigenvalue
 - Rescale variables?

5.1 Random effects

AICtab(m_surv, m_surv2)
        dAIC df
m_surv2 0.0  6 
m_surv  1.5  7

Close to equivalent, so remove plant ID. This makes sense, as plants only die once!

m_surv3 <- glm(surv ~ log_shts + habitat + density_0_10 + density_10_20, 
                family = binomial, data = ha_sub)
AICtab(m_surv2, m_surv3)
        dAIC df
m_surv2  0.0 6 
m_surv3 85.7 5

Cant remove year.

    0.8815508     0.8650570     0.4864617     0.4994200     0.5000884

Marginal, and only immediate grid cell. Density has positive affect on survival. So, probably just good patches.
